# 5 Example 

As an example, consider the core module of the IDHKP-IDH (IDH = isocitrate dehydrogenase, $\mathrm{KP}=$ kinase-phosphatase) glyoxylate bypass regulation system shown in the following reaction scheme:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{E}+\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{p}} \underset{k_{1}^{-}}{\stackrel{k_{1}^{+}}{\rightleftharpoons}} \mathrm{EI}_{\mathrm{p}} \underset{k_{2}^{-}}{\stackrel{k_{2}^{+}}{\rightleftharpoons}} \mathrm{E}+\mathrm{I} \\
& \mathrm{EI}_{\mathrm{p}}+\mathrm{I} \underset{k_{2}^{-}}{\stackrel{k_{2}^{+}}{\rightleftharpoons}} \mathrm{EI}_{\mathrm{p}} \mathrm{I} \underset{k_{4}^{-}}{\stackrel{k_{4}^{+}}{\rightleftharpoons}} \mathrm{EI}_{\mathrm{p}}+\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{p}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Here, I is the IDH enzyme, $\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{p}}$ is its phosphorylated form, and E is the bifunctional enzyme IDH kinase-phosphatase. The system has experimentally been shown to obey approximate concentration robustness in the IDH enzyme I [37]. In $[52,50]$, it was shown that if the CRN obeys mass action kinetics and the rate constants $k_{2}^{-}$and $k_{4}^{-}$are zero, i.e., if the respective fluxes vanish identically, then there is absolute concentration robustness in the IDH enzyme.
